This user has two instances that are separated, he wants to copy issues and boards between instances. As boards are not project specific when following the documentation the issues end up out of the correct order.

 

{quote}

I am Company A with Jira Instance A. I have 3 projects, which are managed together on Scrum Board A. This Scrum board features in Portfolio Plan A. I want to be able to regularly (e.g. weekly) take a snapshot of my projects, Scrum board and Portfolio plan across to Jira Instance B, where company B will view these as if they were read only (i.e. there’s no plan to round-trip or try and make changes in the copy I’ve transferred into Jira Instance B). Company B does all it’s work in Project 4, manages this via Scrum Board B and has Portfolio Plan B to plan releases etc. Both Portfolio plans are viewable on a Programme which gives an overall view of the work and release dates between both companies.

 

I am transferring Projects 1, 2 and 3, with all associated custom fields, and Scrum Board A. The projects and Scrum board are re-created successfully in Jira Instance B after the transfer, but the big problems I’m battling are as per the issue raised in the last comment of this JIRA ticket<https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-28748> (as referenced in my support request):

1. A single sprint in progress on Scrum Board A turns into 3 duplicated sprints (one per project) after transfer to Jira Instance B;
2. The Scrum Board A backlog order (which consisted of a carefully prioritised list of tickets from the 3 projects) loses the order on transfer. It seems issues are imported by project first, so whilst the order within a single project is right, the overall order on the backlog is totally wrong.

{quote}

h2. Actual behaviour

On bards that have a large number of epics (100+) agile boards may be slower up to 50% when compared to Jira 7.4.x.

On our internal tests with a board containing 320 Epics, we see following results:
|Test|metric|View Board|
|Slow boards|average response time|3084|
|Fast boards|average response time|1767|
h2. Expected behaviour

Boards should be performing at least as they did in 7.4 version.
h2. Root cause

In the development of epics in kanplan we have added epics count to allData.json request in Jira Agile. 

The code looks as follows:
{code:java}
ServiceOutcome<EpicData> epicDataServiceOutcome = epicsHelper.loadEpicData(user, rapidView); 
if (epicDataServiceOutcome.isValid()) { 
   workData.epicData.epicsCount = epicDataServiceOutcome.get().epics.size(); 
} {code}
This code is very inefficient, as creating epicDataServiceOutcome on large datasets is very expensive operation. 
h2. Workaround

There is no possible workaround for this issue.

h3. *Expected Behavior*

Backslash Double Quote \" should show Double quote insteaed of ending the string.
h4. Example Code Below

{code:json}
{ "hello": "world \" series"}
{code}
h3. *Actual Behavior*
{code:java}
{ "hello": "world \" series"}
{code}
h3. *Expected Behavior*

{color:#333333}{ {color}{color:#14892c}"hello"{color}{color:#333333}:{color} {color:#14892c}"world " series{color}" }
h3. *Steps to Reproduce*
 # Go to comment text editor
 # Enter Code below
{quote}
{code:java}
{ "hello": "world \" series"}
{code}
{quote}
 # Go to Visual Editor to view the code result

h3. Workaround

No workaround available currently.
